Price chart: MMA Southeast Asia vs PMMA Southeast Asia
Asia spot markets Spot prices of methyl methacrylate (MMA) in Asia Pacific held steady in the week ended 18 November, amidst range-bound discussions.
Regional spot availability remained tight generally, with many producers outside of China heard more preoccupied with replenishing their low inventories.
The supply shortage situation is expected to persist for some time more. There is unlikely any respite from deep-sea supplies, as availabilities in the US and Europe are low to begin with given several plant troubles there in recent times.
Given this, substantive discussions and transactions in bulk cargoes of more than 500 tonnes were scant, as most regional sellers said they did not have sufficient volumes in the first place, to market bulk cargoes.
Sellers were heard maintaining their expectations at around $1,850/tonne CFR SE Asia for bulk cargoes in more than 500 tonnes, as they perceived prices to stay well-supported by the limited supplies. However, the upside potential in prices may be limited, with buyers heard mostly retreating to the sidelines and staving off fresh purchases until the prices soften in due course.
In the absence of concrete transactions, market participants deemed the published price ranges for CFR southeast (SE) Asia, Taiwan and South Korea for bulk cargoes of over 500 tonnes to be workable buy-sell indications if supplies were available.
Discussions on MMA parcels in 20-300 tonnes were comparatively more active, with end-users heard relatively more open to considering such purchases, on a need-to basis, to cover any pressing requirements that may surface in the short term.
Market sources said that there were some 20-300 tonne lot-size transactions completed during the reporting week, in the $1,925-2,000/tonne CFR SE Asia range, although players involved could not be ascertained. The published price range for cargoes of this size was viewed as representative of the broader mainstream market, and the CFR southeast Asia assessment was kept unchanged. That said, many market players said that the spot prices may have plateaued at current levels, as the downstream polymethyl methacrylate (PMMA) sector may not be able to absorb any further increases.
Chinese domestic market Chinese domestic MMA prices in eastern and southern areas continued to soften week-on-week. With most plant maintenance work completed or being wrapped up, operating rates among Chinese plants are expected to incrementally recover. Pricing sentiment dipped as a result, as more supplies surfaced amidst a seasonal lull in demand.

18 November 2016
Methyl Methacrylate Asia Pacific Chemical Prices | News | Analysis Editors: Melanie Wee, Lim Ai Teng
 
 

In India, bulk MMA cargoes were heard sold at around mid $1,800s/tonne CIF India, on a dutiable basis, for early December delivery.
Demand in India for MMA imports was said to be healthy, especially as Indian buyers sought additional supplies to fill a shortfall in deep-sea arrivals. That said, market participants said that it was unclear how the robustness in Indian buying interest may be affected when the impact from the recent governmental decision to demonetise 500 and 1,000 rupee notes sets in on the Indian MMA sector in due course. If the domestic cash crunch situation exacerbated, Indian importers appetite and ability to absorb additional imports at current levels may weaken.
Upstream
Crude futures prices were higher by 1-2% in the week ended 18 November. Prices gained ground amid renewed hopes that OPEC can reach an agreement to curb output at its meeting at the end of November. Attacks on oil facilities in Nigeria also helped buoy prices earlier in the week. Crude values were firmer despite a larger-than-forecast build in US crude stocks and a stronger US dollar.
Downstream related Spot prices of general purpose (GP) grade polymethyl methacrylate (PMMA) in southeast Asia and China were range-bound in the week ended 17 November, amidst steady demand.
(Covering Editor: Ai Teng Lim)
